<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-380-982  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 380 982.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  June 26 1989 v11 n26 p42(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Minnesota invokes computer law: several other states areattempting to implement similar measures.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Rachel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In the wake of the computer virus scare, Minnesota has passed thefirst law aimed at individuals who distribute destructivesoftware.andP;  The Minnesota Computer Virus Crime Bill, which takeseffect Aug 1, 1989, prohibits the 'intentional distribution ofdestructive computer programs.' Any program that producesunauthorized data that simply takes up memory space is alsoconsidered destructive.andP;  Penalties range up to 10 years in prisonand $50,000 in fines.andP;  Maryland and West Virginia recently havepassed computer virus crime bills, and federal computer-viruslegislation has been proposed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Minnesota Computer Virus Crime Act (criminal provisions).andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesLegal IssuesMinnesotaState GovernmentComputer CrimesLegislation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>